summarization.results: Skellig Michael, an island off the west coast of Ireland, housed a Catholic monastery from the 7th to the 12th century. Despite Viking raids, the monks thrived in their remote and extreme environment, practicing a unique form of monasticism influenced by Ethiopian roots. The monks lived in huts on the 800-foot high rock, cultivating crops and seeking solitude for prayer.
